column8:
Wild T & The Spirit
Friday, November 26th 2021
Tickets only $20 advanced.
Get your tickets now by hitting the Find Tickets button or go to our website https://blindbeggar.ca/buy-tickets/

Doors open at 5:30pm.
Show starts 7:30.
Make it dinner and a show: Buy your show tickets and then add on BBQ Pit Platter for your table.
Come for dinner anytime before your show!
Note: when you purchase your table, you own it for the night.
General Admission tickets do not guarantee a seat or table. First come first serve for any unsold tables.
Thanks for supporting us and Live music.
Check out the video below...............
https://youtu.be/JsWb2u2sGGA
BIO:
Guitarist Toney Springer has hung with the best of them, David Bowie, Jeff Healey, Bon Jovi, Jay Leno, David Letterman and Arsenio Hall. These are a few of the personalities that have been blown away by Toney's music.
Toney aka Wild T took his name from his home town of Tunapuna Trinidad, though one may find similarities to Jimi Hendrix, Lenny Kravitz & Eric Gales ironically it was Toney's exposure to Steve Howe (Yes) that inspired him to pick up guitar.
Moving to Toronto in his early teens, Toney quickly gained a reputation in the mid 80's... After being in Toronto for a few years Toney was voted best guitarist at the Canadian Black Music awards and has not looked back since. Jeff Healey saw a man with endless imagination, a man who could combine that imagination with an emotion that you couldn't help but feel. "I followed him around like he was a Messiah, I probably learned more from Toney than anybody else, Toney's been my idol for years" said Jeff Healy.
Jeff Healey wasn't the only one who noticed Toney's rapid ascension through the ranks. David Bowie chose Toney to be his guitarist on his Black Tie White Noise album after seeing Toney's video for 'Midnight Blues' on a tv show while in Montreal with Tin Machine (Bowie's Supergroup), subsequently Toney appeared with Bowie on Jay Leno, David Letterman & Arsenio Hall & on Bowie's making of Black Tie White Noise dvd prominently showcasing Toney.... "an absolute delight to work with" said Bowie.
The spiritual karma exchanged with his audiences has given Toney a tremendous reputation for firey live performances.
www.wildtandthespirit.com

BIO:
Guitarist Toney Springer has hung with the best of them, David Bowie, Jeff Healey, Bon Jovi, Jay Leno, David Letterman and Arsenio Hall. These are a few of the personalities that have been blown away by Toney's music.
Toney aka Wild T took his name from his home town of Tunapuna Trinidad, though one may find similarities to Jimi Hendrix, Lenny Kravitz & Eric Gales ironically it was Toney's exposure to Steve Howe (Yes) that inspired him to pick up guitar.
Moving to Toronto in his early teens, Toney quickly gained a reputation in the mid 80's... After being in Toronto for a few years Toney was voted best guitarist at the Canadian Black Music awards and has not looked back since. Jeff Healey saw a man with endless imagination, a man who could combine that imagination with an emotion that you couldn't help but feel. "I followed him around like he was a Messiah, I probably learned more from Toney than anybody else, Toney's been my idol for years" said Jeff Healy.
Jeff Healey wasn't the only one who noticed Toney's rapid ascension through the ranks. David Bowie chose Toney to be his guitarist on his Black Tie White Noise album after seeing Toney's video for 'Midnight Blues' on a tv show while in Montreal with Tin Machine (Bowie's Supergroup), subsequently Toney appeared with Bowie on Jay Leno, David Letterman & Arsenio Hall & on Bowie's making of Black Tie White Noise dvd prominently showcasing Toney.... "an absolute delight to work with" said Bowie.
The spiritual karma exchanged with his audiences has given Toney a tremendous reputation for firey live performances.
www.wildtandthespirit.com

Rose (Claire Lecocq) and Owl (Jarred Albright) have been playing music together for nearly a decade. They have spent countless hours writing and arranging music and honing their ensemble both on and off the stage.

A seasoned instrumentalist and sideman, Jarred Albright has been performing all over the continent and is a sought-after fiddle player and mandolinist in a multitude of genres and applications. No stranger to the stage herself, Claire Lecocq has been playing and performing music since she was 6 years old, and has lent her vocal talents to numerous recordings.

Rose + Owl is the latest culmination of their favourite styles and influences and draws from their shared love of Old-Time, Bluegrass, Western Swing, Americana, Folk and Roots to create a polished and uniquely unmistakable sound. 

They are currently writing and performing in anticipation of their debut album in 2020.

column5: TOM PHILLIPS with Kit Johnson & Tim Leacock
column8:
The tradition continues at the Ironwood in the Age of Aquarium. Tom Phillips takes the Casat Deck at the Ironwood for the 13th year in a row on Parade Day, joined this year by Kit Johnson and Tim Leacock. Due to limited seating and social distancing requirements, reservations are required. 20$ cover charge. Call 403-269-5581 for reservations. Shine up your boots and come on down!!!

Now more about Tom...

TOM PHILLIPS Calgary, Alberta Band leader. Honky-tonk hero. Even soundtrack writer for a book (a Canadian first, for a Will Ferguson novel.) Survivor and singer of cautionary tales. You want it, you got it from Tom Phillips, whose career’s turned itself inside out so often that at times he appears to be a shape shifter. During the past few years, Phillips’ transformation was also physical as he swapped alcohol for coffee and his trademark cowboy boots and shirts for polished shoes and tailored suits. But appearances distract, and Phillips is no shape shifter: if you took a musical x-ray during every incarnation, you’d find song writing as the bedrock under the suits, boots, cowboy hats and skin. Which explains why revered blues artist Eric Bibb covered Phillips’ touchstone tune, Ribbons and Bows, on one of his albums. An esteemed statesperson of the Calgary music scene, Phillips earned his laurels over decades. He recorded with Gordon Lightfoot’s band in Toronto before releasing several albums, both live and in studio, with his legendary long time honky-tonk band The Men of Constant Sorrow (MOCS). He also released an acoustic solo album, paid homage to Hank Williams on the Sorrow Bound project, and smashed his comfort zone with a daring, darling album of cover songs from punk and rock territory. He’s often found anchoring musical gatherings that celebrate the songs of Haggard, Dylan, Springsteen and Lightfoot. 

The evolution continues on his most recent work with the D.T.’s (Difficult Transitions). The band formed serendipitously at bars and open stages, learning Phillips’ most recent songs onstage just in time for his last record. With MOCS veteran Tim Leacock (The Co-Dependents), Ian Grant (Art Bergmann, Cat Ranch), Geoff Brock and sisters Shaye and Sydney Zadravec, the D.T.’s translate Phillips’ songs into live performances that deliver musical delights which offer style without flash. So take a musical walk with Phillips and gaze at life through his seasoned eyes. He’s got it covered with a hundred songs that undress truths so simple they’re frightening. 

Ever cheated on a lover, driven home drunk, been bucked off your horse, or been the last person in the bar when the lights came up? If you’ve been stranded on the highway, woken up in the wrong bed, walked home barefoot in a ball gown in the morning rain, or wished you could have a re-do on any of these choices, Phillips has a song for you. -  MLW   https://www.tomphillipsmusic.com/

column5: Give a Mile - Cooking up Christmas Flights!
column8:
Join us in bringing people together for the holidays! In this virtual special event hosted by JD Lewis, and brought to you by Give A Mile, Blue Flame Kitchen, Village Brewery, and Cask Global Canning Solutions, you’ll enjoy live music by Pat Moore, delicious food and local beer.

Proceeds from this event will go to Give A Mile, a charity which provides flights for people to visit with a loved one who is critically ill or dealing with palliative illness.  This holiday season we are looking to give 25 flights away.

During this event, you will enjoy a three-course meal provided by Blue Flame Kitchen with Village Brewery beer paired with each course. Don’t eat too quickly, as there will be a chef demonstration that will go along your main course with none other than Blue Flame Kitchen's chef Darcy!

You’ll hear speeches from sponsors, connect with community and ultimately give to a great cause.

column5: DIVA DIVO JAZZ SERIES AT COFFEE CATS CAFE presents Deb Rasmussen (vocals) and Jon Day (piano)
column8:
Back on stage at last!  Join Deb and Jon for an evening of favourite standards and new collaborations.

Deb Rasmussen is a jazz singer and songwriter.   Her CD, “Heart Wide Open” features her own tunes and several well-loved jazz standards.   She has also recorded with the ethno-jazz group “Northern Lights – Altai Khangai”, a collaboration of Canadian jazz and Mongolian traditional musicians.  Deb has studied with Jay Clayton, Sheila Jordon, Cheryl Fisher and Dee Daniels and performed at the Calgary Jazz Festival “Party in the Park”, the Giant Steppes Jazz Festival in Mongolia, Lolita’s, the Ironwood and other venues around Calgary. Web: www.debrasmussen.com  Email:deb@debrasmussen.com 

Jon Day (jdaymusic.com) is a multi-instrumentalist, educator, arranger, and composer. As an accomplished trumpet player, pianist, and educator for two decades, Jon has been a featured artist in a variety of music festivals around the globe, and has had the privilege of sharing the stage with a variety of world-class musicians. In addition to an impressive performance career, Jon is also a respected leader having conducted and composed for a wide variety of ensembles (symphony orchestra, studio orchestra, theatre orchestra, brass bands, brass quartets, big bands, and jazz ensembles) and vocal groups (choirs, quartets, theatre ensembles, and soloists).

Coffee Cats Café comes highly rated for its ambiance, Loza’s wonderful homemade food and the warm welcome and personal care you’ll receive. Plan a great evening of listening to soulful jazz, some of Loza’s home made cuisine & a glass or more of adult beverages. 

Tickets available at Brown Paper Tickets  and Coffee Cats. (Purchase at Cafe/ no phone orders). Limited seating. Coffee Cats Café, 2765 17 Ave SW, Calgary.  Phone: 403-240-1842

column8: FULL CIRCLE hosted by the incomparable Kate Stevens with special guests. Support emerging artists and come out for some great food, hot and cold drinks, and fantastic music!!!

As 2020 draws to a close, we can reminisce about how Albertans have stepped up to make the best of our situation. We found joy in sharing our passions online with audiences that we’ve missed so dearly, and we collaborated in more creative ways than we ever thought possible. We watched as artists from across this province sang their hearts out and shared comfort with us through their music.

Earlier this year, The Government of Alberta, Alberta Music, the National Music Centre (NMC), CKUA, and Stagehand collaborated on the Alberta Spotlight series, a weekly digital concert initiative that showcased over 75 acts from across the province, providing free concerts for people watching from home and support to artists during the pandemic. We’re thrilled to offer one last special holiday concert to close out this year, featuring a variety of Alberta musicians including, George Canyon, Maddie Storvold, K-Riz, Lynn Olagundoye, and Joal Kamps.

Tips to the venue will be distributed to that artists.

*** Update***

As the situation around COVID-19 has now evolved into a declared pandemic, we wanted to provide an update on the CDA’s current policies and the steps that we are taking. The health and safety of our people, and our ability to continue to support the downtown community is of the utmost importance to us. 

Our organization has activated the practice of social distancing to help contain the spread of COVID-19.  As such, the CDA office is closed to the public on a go-forward basis, and all programming and event activities have been cancelled indenfinetly.  Our work will continue online and remotely. We are looking forward to reconnecting in the near future about our relaunch kick-off activities.

Please note, that we will not be accepting any booking requests at this time, our schedule will be released when it is safe to do so for all involved parties.

Thank-you for your patience and support

*NOTE**
Thank you for your support for live music in Calgary! The not-for-profit, all volunteer Music Mile Society of Calgary 
All Tips for this performance goes to the Music Mile Revival Fund for the sole purpose of bringing music back to the Mile. In an effort to support both our venues and our musicians, we will pay local artists to play on Music Mile stages, inside and out, on Friday nights during the post-COVID transitional phase. 

Music is returning to Music Mile once again! As venues begin to re-open
their doors to live audiences and welcome artists back to their stages,
Music Mile is thrilled to announce:

Live from Music Mile: It's Friday Night!

The program showcases five venues every Friday in July, with live music
shows played to in-person audiences and streamed live to music lovers
at home.

column8: Czarkologie is an instrumental ensemble, fusing jazz and classical styles. Pianist/composer Anthony Czarnecki and violinist/conductor Eileen Kosasih founded the group in 2010, and they are joined by as many as five additional musicians. Their all-original music has many inspirations, but is always marked by joyful, rhythmic energy.

Tonight we feature soprano Alyssa Durnie with pianist (and frequent Classical Rev-er) Eileen Kosasih, in a set of arias and songs! We'll also have chamber music contributions from Silverwood Trio and a Brahms Sextet - more details to come!

column8: Blending the vibrant sound of virtuosic violin playing with the exotic, Guatemalan tone of the westernised marimba, this duo will present new sonic settings of music that ranges from the quick and dynamic harmonies of Johann Sebastian Bach to the dark and seductive Latin American take on tango music of Astor Piazolla.

Frequent hosts and performers Matt Heller (double bass) and Joseph Fernando (piano) welcome fall with cozy sets for solo instrumentals. We'll also honour Jacques Loussier, a legendary jazz crossover pianist who passed away this spring, with a set of his mesmerizing reinventions of Bach, featuring Clicquot Trio (Claire Butler, piano; Reuben Grendus, drums; Matt Heller, bass).

Broken City: Kevin Kane (Grapes of Wrath) & The Wilderness *Early Show/$10*
column8:
Doors: 8pm/Kevin Kane: 9pm/The Wilderness: 10pm

KEVIN KANE is a founding member of The Grapes of Wrath. As a solo artist, Kane has released the albums Neighborhood Watch (1996), Timmy Loved Judas Priest (2001), How to Build a Lighthouse (2007) & The Home Version (2011) which sees Kane revisiting songs from The Grapes Of Wrath and previous solo work live in the studio, with just his acoustic guitar for accompaniment.
kevinkanemusic.com / kevinkanemusic.bandcamp.com / FB @Kevin-Kane-9382189345 / IG/TW @kevinkanemusic
----
THE WILDERNESS is a Kingston, ON sextet with a propulsive, potent fusion of indie-rock and heartland punk having played 450+ shows and festivals across North America in the last four years. With band members from across Canada, US and UK, The Wilderness have independently released 10 singles, two EPs, a full-length, 40ish music videos, scored a Top 5 single and Top 20 album at national and BBC radio, given an award and earned comparisons to Bruce Springsteen, Mumford & Sons, The Lumineers.from fans and media. "This is our first time in Western Canada including a really special show in Calgary with Kevin Kane.We're humbled to have the privilege of performing these songs to new audiences for the first time. The Wilderness is the strongest we've ever been and we're absolutely aching to show you.”
thewildernessband.com / FB/IG @thewildernesskingston / TW @TheWildernessON

Tyler Csatari has been singing most of his life, and has been playing piano since 8 years old. He has been involved in the Young Canadians school of performing arts for 7 years, and recently started pursuing music independently. He plays weekly at Renaissance cafe in Strathmore, and is always looking for new ways to push his boundaries.

Dan Rebolledo is a Folk-Soul artist drawing from multiple genres to create exciting, melodic and bluesy songs that connect with people tragedies and triumphs. Garrett Barbuto is a charming and introspective small town kid from Northern Ontario with a strong yet simple voice with something to say.

column8: A distinct flavour of the golden age of Jazz, Hope Mack brings the smooth and sultry style of Billy, Ella & Sarah in to a single package.  Hope has been a lover of Jazz her whole life. Growing up in a musical family she gravitated to the distinct style of the 40-50 & 60's beautiful and unique vocal styles. Hope's smooth and stylistic interpretations of the classic songs from this era will leave you breathless. Backed up by a stellar band including John McRory on guitar, Mark Szabo on bass, and Corey Prediger on drums this group will be sure to set a fun and pleasing atmosphere to any room.

*** Update***

As the situation around COVID-19 has now evolved into a declared pandemic, we wanted to provide an update on the CDA’s current policies and the steps that we are taking. The health and safety of our people, and our ability to continue to support the downtown community is of the utmost importance to us. 

Our organization has activated the practice of social distancing to help contain the spread of COVID-19.  As such, the CDA office is closed to the public on a go-forward basis, and all programming and event activities have been cancelled indenfinetly.  Our work will continue online and remotely. We are looking forward to reconnecting in the near future about our relaunch kick-off activities.

Please note, that we will not be accepting any booking requests at this time, our schedule will be released when it is safe to do so for all involved parties.

Thank-you for your patience and support

column5: Szabo and Ladick - Home at Last
column8:
❤️🎶
Szabo & Ladick - jazz, pop & crossovers: a lifetime of performing and the experience has curated a repertoire that spans genres. 

Kim Szabo and Bill Ladick, both originally from Canada, met in Osaka, Japan, while performing in different venues. Their chance meeting soon resulted in collaborative projects, and the realization that they had actually attended the same college. After Kim left Asia for Europe, they lost contact for many years, until by chance made contact again in Calgary. Once again, an opportunity came for them to reunite, and perform together.

“Home at Last” has a special meaning for both of them, from a reunited friendship, to new performance adventures here at home in Canada.

Szabo & Ladick - Home at Last - this Saturday!
Join Bill Ladick and myself at Vin Room West.
8561 8A Avenue SW    
tel 587-353-8812

Saturday November 27, 7-10pm.
Reservations recommended.
No cover.

column8:
Enjoy live music from Travis Dolter and his Band from the comfort of your vehicle or from a VIP Table! Proceeds go to the Camrose Food Bank!

column8:
Kavian Lazar (born on  july 17, 2000 Sardasht, West Azerbaijan, Iran) is an Iranian musician and actor with the stage name of KvinLzr, who started his professional artistic activity in 2017
​​​​​​​
As a child, he was very interested in art and music, and this music gave him a sense of calm Kavian Lazar started working as a teenager and started his career after receiving professional training.

Finally, in 2017-2018, he immigrated to Venice, Italy to study music professionally and completed his studies there. Kavian was very interested in the acting industry and started acting as a child (from the age of 7), and this led him to move towards it day by day, thus playing a role in many films. He has also worked in music, composing and sounding many films which has played an important role in the success of the films.

After reaching high positions in the acting industry, he became a musician with the help of his relatives and the support of famous people in the great world of music. Kavian's main goal was acting, but he also worked a little in the field of music and at the same time he was active in the field of music. After the release of "Noor", he released many works, including The Night, Bitcoin, Nft and Supreme. He has also released an album called Harmony, which includes 13 tracks. All of these music releases are available on all international music platforms.

After countless successes in Italy, Kavian has a company and music institute called KL Company, which consists of 31 musicians, musicians and composers, most of whom are world famous and prominent people, and a few months ago, the fifth year of the establishment of his company. They celebrated The institute also has branches in Singapore, India, Turkey and Iran. Kavian is currently active in the field of music as well as in the field of acting and is always trying to pursue his artistic goals.

column8:
The brass party band that everyone wants to dance to!

We are a quirky, joyful, exuberant brass band. LBJB revels in providing a fun and unique perspective on dance tunes, and we take pride in ensuring our audiences have a fantastic time – with a few laughs along the way!

We are a group of musicians with fine arts degrees, music degrees, and post-secondary music training who insist on having a fun, co-creative, collaborative environment with like-minded (and like-experienced) individuals to complement our ever-evolving lives. Little Brown Jug Brass is comprised of people who take their craft seriously, but not much else!  Having been caught up in the ‘perfectionism’ of it all, we have now chosen to focus on some of the best gifts music has provided us – camaraderie, light-heartedness, connection, and laughter.

column5: Ironwood Grand Re-Opening, Featuring The Blackbelts
column8:
2020 marks the 15th year of operation for the Ironwood Stage and Grill and the 10th year at our current location, the historic Garry Theatre in Inglewood. In that time the Ironwood has established a solid reputation for being one of the finest venues of its size hosting live music in Canada. We are a favourite stop of many national and international touring artists.

In a typical year, the Ironwood plays hosts to over 400 music performances. In 2020 the final total will certainly fall well below that number. On March 17, we reluctantly had to close our doors, complying with the provincial government’s directive to help limit the spread of the Coronavirus. 

This Saturday night, June 20, The Ironwood will reopen and once again offer its audience a full, true, and unique live music experience, while remaining fully compliant with Phase 2 of the Provincial Government’s COVID-19 General Relaunch Guidance. We have  retooled our backstage, behind the renowned Casat Deck Stage to incorporate a separate glassed performing area, fully visible to the audience. Vocalists will perform from the confines of this space, safely separated from the rest of their bandmates and audience, yet fully visible and audible to all.

The musical group performing this Saturday night will be The Blackbelts, a Calgary-based Funk/Blues/Soul/Jazz trio featuring two of Calgary’s finest A-List music scene veterans, Jory Kinjo and Aaron Young, as well as veteran drummer, Steve Jackson, a recent import from Philadelphia.

Seating is less than normal due to the restrictions imposed by the GOA’s coronavirus social distancing requirements. Seats must be reserved in advance (403.269.5581) and patrons are encouraged to attend in groups where possible. There will be a cover TBD. A limited menu of Ironwood favourites will be available for your dining pleasure.

column8:
ACT 1: HOLIDAY RADIO PLAY: IT’S AN OKAY LIFE, CONSIDERING
Watch someone’s life transformed this holiday season! This unique show takes its cue from the radio plays popularized in the 1930s and 40s, and from the magic of Frank Capra’s classic film It’s a Wonderful Life.

This completely improvised radio play features live actors, made up stories, improvised product sponsor ads, and live music and sound effects!

Featuring live performances from Mandy Morris and her jazz quartet! Produced in partnership with CJSW.

 

ACT 2: GROUP CHAT FEAT. VLAD & VICKY
Are you perpetually glued to your phone?
Do you create insurmountable barriers to your interpersonal communication skills?
Are you unable to form intimate connections the old-fashioned way?
Same! Group Chat is a troupe of tech-savvy artists who perform improv inspired by your favourite social media platforms – from the trending Tweets to Skype calls with your mom!

Watch these Millennials cope with crushing debt and imminent ecological disaster by laughing at the absurdity of our modern existence!

Tickets for this very special show are $15 each. Students 2-for-1 at the door, with student ID.

Online sales end at 6pm day of the show. A limited number of tickets will be available at the door – we open at 7:30pm.

The Inglewood Night Market is a modern day market that occurs on a Friday once a month, from June to September in Calgary Alberta.

In 2019 our dates are June 7th, July 12th, August 9th, September 13th and September 14th (In September we do two nights both Friday and Saturday) we run from 5pm to 11pm each date.

Each event hosts over 50 local vendors selling diverse goods from handmade craftsmen items to vintage clothing, antiques & collectibles, artisan eats & more! You’ll also find food trucks, singer songwriters, bands, dancers, outdoor seating, a family friendly licensed area and other fun things to check out!

Our home is the beloved Inglewood Neighborhood just off 9th Avenue and 10th street!

column5: Two Late To The Party with Wild Rose Robinson
column8:
Welcome to Koi Patio Sessions!
Come enjoy our NEW menu, and some delicious drinks while enjoying live entertainment!
All artists will be performing inside of the Koi space, through the window to the patrons on the patio for a completely Covid safe environment.
Patrons are asked to still please bring and wear masks whenever they are not seated at their tables.
Reservations are HIGHLY recommended during show times - you can book online through our website
www.koicalgary.com/reservations or by calling 403-206-1564 during business hours 4-10pm
This is a FREE SHOW - DONATIONS WILL BE ACCEPTED FOR ARTISTS - CASH OR ELECTRONICALLY ON YOUR BILL
Saturday July 3
Two Late to the Party is a Calgary based folk duo who's music has been played across Canada. Their latest singles "R-V-M" and "Ghost in my bones" have been featured on Calgary's X929.9 Xposure, Alberta's CKUA radio, their debut album "The Great Unraveling" has been ranked Top 50 albums by Earshot Daily and Top 30 albums for CJSR Edmonton, CHRW London and CFRU Guelph!
Formed by Adam Corkett and Alessandra Enns in the fall of 2017. Both Adam and Alessandra have a long singer/songwriter history, with influences ranging from indie-folk to bluegrass-country. As a pair, they have found a style that merges their past influences, creating an original sound that is simultaneously current and nostalgic. In 2018, Two Late to the Party released music videos for their songs “In Gold” and “Divine”. In the spring of 2019, Two Late to the Party released their first single “Here With Me”.
Wild Rose Robinson is a band with rotating instrumentalists led by a queer, female vocalist and songwriter. They sing songs that are stories in which you can be the main character, whoever you are.
We acknowledge that this territory is home to the Métis Nation of Alberta, Region 3 within the historical Northwest Métis homeland. Finally, we acknowledge all Nations – Indigenous and non – who live, work and play on this land, and who honour and celebrate this territory.

column5: Fort Calgary Presents: Amelie Patterson and Sargeant & Comrade
column8:
Fort Calgary is thrilled to showcase a fierce double bill featuring Amelie Patterson and Sargeant & Comrade. This special event promises to be an unforgettable, intimate concert, including a meet and greet following the performance.


TICKET INCLUDES:

Assigned seating in our intimate Burnswest Theatre
A private post-show meet and greet with the artists, including complimentary beverages from Village Brewery and Rithet Coffee
Complimentary access to Fort Calgary's Interpretive Centre

Licensed event.

Tickets available online or at the door. 

Paid parking available on-site.

Please note that assigned seating is not guaranteed once the doors are closed. 

*****

About the Artists
AMELIE PATTERSON

Hailing from Banff, Alberta, and serving as the town’s first Poet Laureate, Amelie Patterson leads as a strong ambassador for women songwriters. The clear-voiced, honest and tenacious troubadour’s music traverses territories from blues to folk rock. Her debut album Roll Honey Roll was released in May 2016 at Canadian Music Week and went on to win YYC Alternative Recording of The Year in 2017. Patterson then took to the road touring across Canada hitting stages at Calgary Folk Music Festival, Banff Centre for Arts and Creativity, TED Talks, and venues across Alberta and BC.

www.ameliepattersonmusic.com


SARGEANT & COMRADE

One from Russia, one from Carribean, Sargeant & Comrade (Yolanda Sargeant & DJ Comrade) combine various cultures, styles and genres to create a unique sound that has been captivating audiences since this unlikely duo began playing live shows in 2009. Sargeant & Comrade combine elements of old school jazz, soul, reggae and hip hop to create brand new flavours of music that transcend genre. Dusty record samples get mixed with live instruments and Yolanda Sargeant’s stylish, soulful voice brings it all together. 

www.soundcloud.com/yolandasargeant

column8: Born & raised in Calgary Alberta, Phenix's songs tell of the faith, love & loss found between the open prairies & towering Rocky Mountains of Southern Alberta. Phenix’s distinct sound is grounded in lush acoustic guitars, lo-fi basement recordings, nostalgic drum sounds & winding pedal steel. His debut album Nothing But The Blood, intertwines ideas of love, christianity & self acceptance in a unique & mature way for a first release. Phenix also produces records with artists such as Heather May, Luke Nielsen, Wyatt C Louis & others across the Canadian music scene at his studio in Calgary “Alta Sound”.

column8:
To Friends and Family of the Ironwood, 

When we lose a venue in Calgary, we lament it's loss and wish we could've done something to save a place that we cherish and value so dearly. We wish we could've done SOMEthing to save it. 

The time is now to come to the aid of our beloved Ironwood. They have but a few months before they are forced to close the doors permanently. We all understand these are unprecedented times in our Arts community. We cannot afford to lose this venue that is so vital and crucial to our City's music scene. 

More efforts will be done, rest assured, but for now we are throwing a fundraiser to show Pat, Amanda and the rest of the gang how much they mean to us and how much we love the Ironwood. 

All artists have donated their time to the efforts and we have received a flood of support from the community for our silent auction as well. 

Need to know:
YES - you can buy a table and attend the shows
call 403-269-5581 for a table 
YES - you can donate/support online directly! 
more details to come on that
YES - There will be future shows and events in support
YES - you can come by and bid on the silent auction and not attend the show (it will be in the lobby)

TICKETS: 
Friday Aug 21 - $50 **all proceeds going to the ironwood**
Saturday, Aug 22 Matinee 1:00PM - $30
Saturday, Aug 22 - $50 Evening show 8:00 PM

column8:
To Friends and Family of the Ironwood, 

When we lose a venue in Calgary, we lament it's loss and wish we could've done something to save a place that we cherish and value so dearly. We wish we could've done SOMEthing to save it. 

The time is now to come to the aid of our beloved Ironwood. They have but a few months before they are forced to close the doors permanently. We all understand these are unprecedented times in our Arts community. We cannot afford to lose this venue that is so vital and crucial to our City's music scene. 

More efforts will be done, rest assured, but for now we are throwing a fundraiser to show Pat, Amanda and the rest of the gang how much they mean to us and how much we love the Ironwood. 

All artists have donated their time to the efforts and we have received a flood of support from the community for our silent auction as well.

column5: BEAUTY LOVE TRUTH FEAT. EMILY TRIGGS | DREAM TOAST
column8:
ACT 1: BEAUTY LOVE TRUTH FEAT. EMILY TRIGGS
Beauty Love Truth combines live music and heartfelt improv. Performing scenes inspired by original songs, the improvisers bring new meaning to the lyrics through tales of heartbreak, happiness and hope.

FEATURING GUEST MUSICIAN EMILY TRIGGS
Emily Triggs is a prolific songwriter with a passion for storytelling.  Sometimes likened to Patty Griffin and Michelle Shocked, Emily’s unique brand of folk/roots showcases her honest, pure vocals.

Emily’s debut album ‘When Guinevere Went Under’, received radio play across the country and into the United States. Emily has performed at CBC, Vancouver Folk Music Festival, Calgary Folk Music Festival and Wide Cut Weekend. With her soon-to-be-released album, ‘Middletown, ’Triggs is busting down walls that confine an artist to expectations and genres.

ACT 2: DREAM TOAST
A show based entirely on dream logic where dreams inspire dreams inspire dreams. It gets weird, nothing makes sense and your mom is there with a different face, but in the end it all means something. Delve into your subconscious with Dream Toast and discover the zany world of dream “logic.”

column5: Live at the Ironwood - ROOKS - Canadian Rock & Roll
column8:
Been far too long since our Casat Deck Stage rocked the way it's gonna rock this Friday Night. Time to rectify the situation and put our Age of Aquarium sound booth to the max test. The Ironwood is very pleased to announce we have ROOKS playing our first live Friday night in 101 Days!

Seating is limited to be compliant with COVID-19 restrictions so reserve early. Cover $15 403.269.5581 A limited menu of Ironwood favourites will be available for your dining pleasure. 

Now about ROOKS... 

ROOKS is a 3 piece rock band which formed in Calgary, Alberta, Canada in July 2018. The band features Jay Bowcott on guitar and vocals, Darryl Swart on drums and Brent Rossall on bass. Their sound is unapologetic guitar rock, drawing influences from bands like Thin Lizzy, The Rolling Stones and The Black Keys.

Originally called Bowcott and the New World, the band are established members of the Canadian music scene and were introduced by ex-The Daggersguitarist, Chris Walsh, who was working with both Swart and Bowcott on separate projects. “I was looking for a drummer for a new album I was working on and Chris suggested that Darryl would be a perfect fit,” says Jay. 

After their first meeting, things developed quickly and within a few months, they had added Brent on bass and recorded a 4 song EP called Extended Play Number 1. “It started out as a solo project but I realized really quickly that everyone was contributing equally so we decided to make it a band.” 

After a whirlwind year touring western and central Canada, the band headed back into the studio in October 2019 to record their debut full-length album which coincided with their name change. “People struggled to know how to pronounce our name and we even got confused for New Order (the 80S British band) once.” laughs Swart. 

“From day one I was uncomfortable with my name being in the band name, so Brent suggested the name ROOKS and it immediately stuck. It has a personal meaning to us and some great imagery which inspired the sound on the new album,” adds Jay.

City of Calgary Anti-Racism Team, Public Safety, and Core Connections Resource Table - Bow Valley College
column8:
The City of Calgary acknowledges the existence of systemic racism. We will listen, learn, and build communities where racialized people and communities have equitable access to City services and programs.

Meeting public safety challenges requires the entire community to come together to better understand our strengths, our challenges, and our shared commitment. We intend to facilitate conversations within and between organizations by fostering a collaborative environment. As we collect input from the community, we will use it to shape further conversations and inform additional engagement.

Adjusting to life in a new country can be challenging. The Core Connections Program (C2) provides a fun space for youth who have recently arrived in Canada to integrate into the community and meet other youth. Core Connections is an ongoing program and focuses on the areas of community engagement, skill-building, and peer mentorship.

column8: Singer-songwriter Ellen Adams works in folk and country traditions, with songs exploring longing, queerness, and the lies we tell ourselves and others in love. Drawing on the influences of Gillian Welch, Whiskeytown, old time, plus some Motown, she brings a little bit of twang and a whole lot of heart to the stage. She's performed in folk festivals and major cities on both sides of North America. Currently, she's artist-in-residence at University of Lethbridge's Gushul Studio, where she's recording her next album.

column8: Geoff McKenzie writes songs that are about something: Love and its malfunctions, theatrical revenge, candied moonlight, at least one murder ballad and the plot of a drugstore novel set to rhyme. It’s hard to tell if he’s a disgraced poet who got good at guitar, or verse vice-a, but somewhere along the line he raised a brood of restless folk songs that will jump in your lap and seize hold of your feelings. The little bastards.

If you'd like to be added to our artists' list, you'll be first to hear about future opportunities like our Songwriting Contest, street artist programs, To Go videos and more. column8: Megan Dawson: "I am a singer/songwriter, playing my guitar and trying to make the world smile one song at a time. I have performed my original music at multiple venues throughout the city such as, Gravity Espresso and Wine Bar, Cowboys Casino Calgary, Ranchman’s Dancehall and many others. Following recording original songs at OCL Studios, I am very excited to release new music in the coming year for you all to hear."\r\n\r\nWe’re Jess & Robb, a girl, a guy, & acoustic guitars. “Dueting” in music and as a couple for the past two years has been wild! We celebrated the release of our self-titled debut EP in July at Café Koi. Since then, we’ve had the opportunity to perform around Calgary,  travel to Nashville for the CD Baby DIY musician conference, and play on the infamous Bluebird Café stage. Our music reflects the pop sensibilities of Taylor Swift, nonchalance of The Ramones, and the wit and heartbreak of Amy Winehouse. We can’t wait to connect and share our music and experiences with you!

column8: Come down to the Ironwood Stage on Thursday, Nov. 17, to catch this band I play with. Musicians from Iran, Syria, Turkey, Chile and Russia, playing traditional instruments (Santur, Oud, Saz) combined with electric bass, guitar, woodwinds and percussion. With original compositions and vocals in Arabic, Turkish, Kurdish and Spanish. It's a really cool, exotic sound that will take you on a musical journey. Plus we'll have a special guest, Flamenco dancer Anastassiia Alexander. It's going to be a great night. 7 pm start. Come for dinner and show!

column8:
BANDing Together II : This One’s For the Venues!

Sponsored by Long & McQuade (Calgary) and Stagehand

This upcoming September 18th, 19th and 20th will see The Ironwood Stage and Grill host a second benefit concert weekend of 15 artists/bands performing on the iconic Casat Deck stage, to further support Calgary venues through this unprecedented time.

Artist Lineup
8:00 – 8:35 pm – Justine Vandergrift (solo)
8:45 – 9:25 pm – The Steve Fisher Band
9:45 – 10:25 pm – The Toques
10:45 – 11:25 pm – Red Hot Hayseeds
11:45 – 12:30 am – Brent Tyler

To buy tix/tables (2-6) & attend call 403.269.5581

Like the first event - BANDing Together II: This One’s For the Venues - will include a very special silent auction, with countless patrons, artists, businesses, restaurants, and the whole arts community coming together to donate unique and diverse items for auction. Along with that, the show will be live streamed for those who prefer to view and donate from their own homes.

Link to GoFundMe Page for donations:
gf.me/u/yxsi9d

Link to Livestream and Stagehand page for Donations:
https://www.stagehand.app/events

Link to Elevate Auctions online auction:
http://m.elevateauctions.com/ironwood2

To donate an item for the auction: Call Amanda at 403.269.5581

For all media inquiries, including interviews with Pat MacIntyre and the performers, please contact:

Scott Morin

Come listen to and support the guitar students of the Legacy Gift of Music program. Since 2006, Legacy has been working hard to create all-inclusive music programming in Alberta that engages financially challenged families and vulnerable and at risk children and youth in potential life altering experiences.\r\n\r\nThrough the Gift of Music we have witnessed the powerful draw that music has for these young people and how significant this program has been in shaping the lives of this community's most vulnerable populations.

Mezzo-Soprano Bethany Yon holds a Masters of Music from Western University in London, Ontario having studied with Torin Chiles and a Bachelor of Music from Ambrose University in Calgary, Alberta. Excited about the world of classical singing, Bethany has embraced advanced study opportunities with Accademia Europea Dell'Opera (AEDO), The Centre for Opera Studies in Italy (COSI), as well as Edmonton, Alberta’s Opera NUOVA and Calgary’s Cowtown Opera Summer Academy. \r\n\r\nEileen Kosasih is inspired by aesthetics and stories.  Her journey includes music study in Calgary, Boston, Indianapolis, Philadelphia, New York City, and L.A.  She has a B.A. Music (violin), M.Music (orchestral conducting), and piano diploma. Eileen is also an artist, busker, music teacher, raver, and curator.  She is founder of Calgary Arts Orchestra, an ensemble that was dedicated to performing new local classical music.

Taylor Thomas is a talented musician with acoustic soul and pop-rock influences. She delivers melodic vocals and memorable performances. She has been featured on radio and preformed in a variety of festivals and venues across Western Canada. Audiences are sure to enjoy the pure passion and love Taylor has for music. Angelic vocals paired with a sultry delivery makes Taylor a MUST see.

column8: Brother Mose is a singer-songwriter out of Calgary, with roots in folk & soul. Influenced by the likes of Bruce Springsteen, Al Green, and Ray Lamontagne, expect raw, earthy tones & honey bourbon melodies.\r\n\r\nBella White is a Calgary based folk singer and songwriter. Having grown up around bluegrass and old-time music it was very clear to her at a young age that she wanted to play music. She now has cultivated a folk sound with influences from country, bluegrass, old-time, and alternative music.

column8: Jiggity James is a country-folk artist with roots in Guelph, Ontario and Calgary, Alberta. His sound is a hearty blend of country western, rag-time and bluegrass, drawing on influences from favourites such as Neil Young, Elvis, Pokey LaFarge, and Old Crow Medicine Show.

Calgary based singer-songwriter, Kearstin Pfeifer was born and raised in southern Saskatchewan and from a young age has had a passion for music. Outside of school, most of her days were spent teaching guitar lessons, participating in band and choir, and leading worship at her church. After high school, Kearstin continued to pursue music at Prairie College in the Music & Worship Arts program where she was mentored by Juno Award winning songwriter, Brian Doerksen. 
​
Kearstin's latest single Yahweh (Hear Your Name)" is nominated for Inspirational//Holiday Song of the Year at the 2022 YYC Awards
​
Kearstin's song "In the Quiet", co-written with Zac Parkinson was nominated for Folk Song of the Year at the 2020 GMA Covenant Awards and her debut EP "The Road Untold" was nominated for Best Saskatchewan Album of the year in 2019."

column5: BANDing Together II: JAZZ NIGHT featuring - Allison Lynch, Johnny Summers Quartet, Angela Wrigley Trio (Single release party!), Redbone Trio, and Johanna Sillanpaa
column8:
BANDing Together II : This One’s For the Venues!

Sponsored by Long & McQuade (Calgary) and Stagehand

This upcoming September 18th, 19th and 20th will see The Ironwood Stage and Grill host a second benefit concert weekend of 15 artists/bands performing on the iconic Casat Deck stage, to further support Calgary venues through this unprecedented time.

(JAZZ NIGHT)
6:00 – 6:35 pm - Allison Lynch
6:45 – 7:25 pm - Johnny Summers Quartet
7:45 – 8:25 pm - Angela Wrigley Trio (Single release party!)
8:45 – 9:25 pm - Redbone Trio
9:45 – 10:30 pm - Johanna Sillanpaa

To buy tix/tables (2-6) & attend call 403.269.5581

Like the first event - BANDing Together II: This One’s For the Venues - will include a very special silent auction, with countless patrons, artists, businesses, restaurants, and the whole arts community coming together to donate unique and diverse items for auction. Along with that, the show will be live streamed for those who prefer to view and donate from their own homes.

Link to GoFundMe Page for donations:
gf.me/u/yxsi9d

Link to Livestream and Stagehand page for Donations:
https://www.stagehand.app/events

Link to Elevate Auctions online auction:
http://m.elevateauctions.com/ironwood2

To donate an item for the auction: Call Amanda at 403.269.5581

For all media inquiries, including interviews with Pat MacIntyre and the performers, please contact:

Scott Morin
scottmorin@me.com
403-690-4747 – Cell

column8: Calgary's Bebo Grove is a three-piece band formed in 2015 by long-time friends and collaborating musicians and songwriters, Jason Selby and Jeff Ragan.  With the addition of Jordan Clermont , a local singer-songwriter, on vocals, the three created a sound that combines a unique blend of styles to create a melodic, emotive sound.  Their music is heavily influenced by a variety of songwriters, bands, and genres, combining poetic lyrics with an energetic fusion of folk, world music, and alternative indie rock.

column5: Two Late To The Party - Rosebud Outdoor Concert Series
column8:
Tickets are $25
Call 1-800-267-7553 to book

Two Late To The Party

Two Late to the Party is a Calgary based folk duo who's music has been played across Canada. Their latest singles "R-V-M" and "Ghost in my bones" have been featured on Calgary's X929.9 Xposure, CKUA radio and their debut album "The Great Unraveling" has been ranked top 10 Folk, Roots, Blues albums by CJSR in Edmonton.

Formed by Adam Corkett and Alessandra Enns in the fall of 2017. Both Adam and Alessandra have a long singer/songwriter history, with influences ranging from indie-folk to bluegrass-country. As a pair, they have found a style that merges their past influences, creating an original sound that is simultaneously current and nostalgic. In 2018, Two Late to the Party released music videos for their songs “In Gold” and “Divine” and in 2019, they released their first single “Here With Me”.

In 2021 TLTTP has started working on their sophomore album which will be releasing later this year.

Rosebud Outdoor Concert Series

The Rosebud Festival Society has teamed up with Rosebud Theatre to put on a special concert experience. On Saturdays in July and August, with a few special Sunday performances, musicians from across Alberta will be travelling to Rosebud to perform live! These concerts will be presented to a physically distanced audience on Rosebud’s gorgeous outdoor stage next to the Opera House.

column5: SCOTT MORIN presents JAZZSEXY with Himself, JOHNNY SUMMERS, KODI HUTCHINSON, SHELDON ZANDBOER, JIM JOHNSTON & guest vocalist ANGELA WRIGLEY
column8:
Calgary, AB - This Sunday, September 5th will see Calgary’s most beloved live music venue continue their deep support for jazz and soulful music with the 2021 premiere of JAZZSEXY. Jazzsexy @ The Ironwood is a monthly celebration of soulful and groove-oriented jazz music, led by many of the leading musicians in the Calgary music community.
Nearly 10 years ago, Jazzsexy was borne out of the live-work loft of 3 Time Juno Award winning Producer, saxophone player and record label veteran Scott Morin. Back in 2012, Scott moved into a scrawling, 3000 ft. loft in the heart of Toronto’s entertainment district, near King and Bathurst. The Niagara Street loft was on the main floor of a massive warehouse building built in the 1880’s, one of the last of the illegal live-work artist warehouses in Toronto, and the former factory for the Heintzman piano company and a large coffin manufacturer in the early 1900s. In modern times, the warehouse became the home to dozens of visual artists, actors, musicians, poets and even a downstairs BDSM “dungeon”.! In addition, it was across the street from famed Director Atom Egoyan’s home, which led it to be included in some of his most famous films in various location scenes. The vibrancy of the arts community was alive on Niagara Street, and led to the inspiration resulting in a monthly jazz party at 91 Niagara Street, Scott’s home and creative space.
This monthly party soon became one of the most talked-about underground music events in Toronto, with celebrities, local news anchors, local and international musicians coming down to hang, sit in, and dig the music. The vibe of these parties was always celebratory – there was a 25 foot curved bar, a huge stage with grand piano and room for a large band, jazz awards and classic jazz photography from Paul Hoefler on the walls, and antique furniture all over the loft for folks to sit and enjoy the music from. Everyone from Grammy and Juno winners Roy Hargrove, Jeff ‘Tain’ Watts, Seamus Blake, Ron Sexsmith, JP Saxe, and dozens of others from the Toronto and NYC jazz communities came in to Jazzsexy to be part of the experience and play.
The name “Jazzsexy” came from Scott’s love of Jazz and the music of Prince. Prince recorded a legendary record in 1988 called “Lovesexy” which is where the brand for the concert series began. Prince’s spirit lives on through Jazzsexy concerts now, including arrangements of some of the geniuses’ classic songs.
Since moving back home from two decades living in Toronto, NYC and Vancouver, Scott Morin has been promoting and playing jazz and soulful music around Calgary as a secondary career, but is now focusing on a number of live music initiatives in Calgary, starting off with Jazzsexy @ The Ironwood!

Little Ole Wine Drinker (the artist formerly known as Mark Cassano) is a guitarist/singer/songwriter based in Calgary. Think of him as the metaphorical musical love child of Nat King Cole and Dolly Parton.....  hmm... how about Willie Nelson and Norah Jones? Maybe Julie London and Lyle Lovett? Okay... that is not getting any less creepy, but you get the idea. His original songs are a blend of folk and jazz with a touch of blues and country. His set list consists of songs that he loves listening to and learning - and, here's the challenge, songs that he can do some semblance of justice to. They range from classic jazz standards to old time country to Americana. And he will make sure to play his wide variety of homemade mid-life crisis ballads and anthems. Recording will begin on his first solo album - he promises... soon...... he swears..... yep.....

column5: Szabo and Ladick - Home at Last
column8:
Szabo & Ladick - jazz, pop & crossovers: a lifetime of performing and the experience has curated a repertoire that spans genres. 

Kim Szabo and Bill Ladick, both originally from Canada, met in Osaka, Japan, while performing in different venues. Their chance meeting soon resulted in collaborative projects, and the realization that they had actually attended the same college. After Kim left Asia for Europe and Bill moved on to Singapore, they lost contact for many years, until by chance made contact again in Calgary. Once again, an opportunity came for them to reunite, and perform together.

“Home at Last” has a special meaning for both of them, from a reunited friendship, to new performance adventures here at home in Canada.

Szabo and Ladick at Vin Room West

column8:
Performance is still happening at Koi THIS Saturday ❤️🎶

Szabo & Ladick - jazz, pop & crossovers: a lifetime of performing and the experience has curated a repertoire that spans genres. 

Kim Szabo and Bill Ladick, both originally from Canada, met in Osaka, Japan, while performing in different venues. Their chance meeting soon resulted in collaborative projects, and the realization that they had actually attended the same college. After Kim left Asia for Europe, they lost contact for many years, until by chance made contact again in Calgary. Once again, an opportunity came for them to reunite, and perform together.

“Home at Last” has a special meaning for both of them, from a reunited friendship, to new performance adventures here at home in Canada.

Szabo & Ladick - Home at Last - this Saturday. 
Join Bill Ladick and myself szabo at Koi 
THIS Saturday Sept 18, 7-10PM.

Reservations recommended. 
Call 403-206-1564.
1011 1 St SW

Cover: "Pay what you Wish". 
Please support live music wherever you can.
See you there!

column8: Headed up by childhood friends Jenna and Charity, Meadow Drive hails from Calgary, Alberta. Due to their vast range of musical influences, the band's distinct sound is a direct result of the unique playing style of each member, rather than their alignment with any particular genre. The band's jazz roots are apparent in the harmonic structure of the songs and melodic importance of the bass, while their love of funk and disco often shines through with crisp, clean guitar riffs and syncopated grooves. Smooth, yet powerful vocals bring even their rock influenced repertoire under the umbrella of the sound they call their own.\r\nCalvin has always been writing music, even as a young kid.  He found his home in hardcore/metal bands as a youth, but he always had his own acoustic songs going on in the background.  Although he lived in Australia at the time, he was inspired by the bleak and dreary winter landscapes of his Canadian home, and slowly put an album together.  Upon moving home, he enlisted a best friend, his sister and his wife, and The Great Grey was born.

“Songbird Concert” 

Ironwood Stage & Grill
Calgary, AB
Saturday February 5, 2022
Reservations 403.269.5581
Limited seating 

It’s heartfelt, it’s inspiring, it’s captivating! This show is a must see with Shari’s interpretations of songs spanning decades by many of the world’s greatest icons. This songbird’s style is soulful/pop with beautiful jazz influences. If you love music by Gershwin, Adele, Carole King, Stansfield and more then get ready to be taken on a musical journey!
Shari will share her past and present music influences as well as debut her original single, co-written with Jon Day that will be released in March!
Joining Shari on stage with their incredible chemistry are musical director, arranger and keyboardist JON DAY with the combinations of the soulful jazz fusions of Rob Hutchinson on bass and Sanah Kadoura on drums.
 
This will be a sensational night with her return to the Ironwood Stage!

column8: Jessica Heaven crosses genres to create meaningful and powerful art forms. She has worked with Juno Award-winning composer Jordan Nobles on multiple occasions, including the Canada Music Week in 2012 and his project "Chiaroscuro". She has released several albums including "Primal Navigation"; "Caught in a Memory"; "A Descartes Christmas Volume 1 & 2", and "Descartes for Sheila" honouring the great Sheila Jordan. She is also the Chair of the Women in Jazz Association of BC, is a board delegate for the Seattle Women in Jazz, and is a member the leadership team for the Sister Jazz Orchestra.

column8:
Ms. Oäi is an African born Jazz Singer based out of Calgary. Her music has the jazz underpinnings of Ella Fitzgerald, and Sarah Vaughn.  While bringing on her own NeoSoul emotional connection and the depth and emotions of love, heartbreak, and the current climate.

Ms. Oäi’s voice unique tone, adds layers of simple but rich technical nuances allowing her to perform and connect with the audience on a deeper level. Her witty on stage banter with the band invites you in.

Her band — Bryan Biblock on drums is a steward on the drums, Ben Tizzard on guitar is a technical wizard on guitar, and introducing Julia Brown on Bass a step above others in her style.  With Ms. Oäi and her quartet You will find yourself immersed, uplifted and ready for a new day.

I am happy to be part of a Fundraiser for Hurricane Fiona that ravaged the East Coast.

On September 24 and 25, 2022, Hurricane Fiona swept through Atlantic Canada and part of Quebec, causing heavy rain and high winds. Impacts included flooding, road washouts, downed trees, utility outages, and damage to coastal infrastructure.

I have the privilege of playing November 13th at 2 PM @ Top’s Pizza.  Please come enjoy some good music and support our fellow Canadians through this hardship 🙏

column5: Two Late to the Party with Natalie Inga
column8:
Join Calgary folk roots band Two Late To The Party and singer songwriter Natalie Inga for a night of original music and fun at Gravity Espresso and Wine Bar in Inglewood. 

Two Late To The Party has recently released their new single “All I Want Is Love” as part of their upcoming sophomore album “In The Sunrise”. Two Late To The Party performs their original music that ranges heartfelt to an uptempo indie-folk sound with lyrics that are meaningful with a deep folk vibe.

Natalie Inga is a Songwriter and Musician based in Calgary, AB. Earthy, spunky, and fierce, Natalie is a confluence of traits that make for bold, reflective, and graceful music, and an intimate, humorous live show. Raised on Canada's greatest folk music, Natalie brings a modern perspective to the tradition of writing for change. Because of her sweet voice, stacked harmonies, rich guitar parts, and bold messages, her most recognized influence is Joni Mitchell.

column5: Mason Jenkins with opener Cyd Hall.
column8: For Cyd Hall, words have always been a comfort. Whether it’s listening to someone’s story or spilling her own thoughts, the act is therapeutic. She uses music to convey that energy and pushes the love back into the universe. She’s just stepping into the incredible YYC art scene and will enjoy the adventure, wherever it may lead.\r\n\r\nMason's songs are velvet paintings. They are elegantly grafted and from a forgotten era and delightfully campy. His songwriting is built upon on a darkness that makes the listener ask out loud "...hey, is this guy ok?" He most definitely is, but it's best to come find out for yourself.

column8: 2018 YYCMusic Awards Female Artist of the Year, Kate Stevens is an 18 year-old emerging artist who has been immersed in music her entire life. While scavenging through a garage sale, Kate found a used ukulele - a tool that shaped her music journey over the past 6 years. Her blended genre sound is an eclectic mix of emotive folk and soulful jazzy pop, with major influences from timeless voices such as Etta James, Ella Fitzgerald, and Joni Mitchell. Stevens likes to describe her sound as if Amy Winehouse and Carole King had a lovechild"\r\nHer unique soulful melodies are advanced yet approachable and truly heartfelt. Kate’s latest singles, "Right Choice" and  "it's real" follow her debut EP Handmade Rumours from June 2017. Kate is a powerful and engaging performer that captivates audiences of all ages. Kate is also the recipient of the 2018 Zachariah and the Prophets Memorial Award.

column5: Classical Rev YYC presents Revolutionary String Quartets
column8:
our instruments, eight hands, sixteen strings — it all adds up one of the most complex, versatile, and astonishing ensembles ever invented. Classical Revolution Calgary celebrates the string quartet, with an evening featuring music by Beethoven and other revolutionary composers!

Four young string players from the Calgary Philharmonic have recently formed a quartet, and this will be a early opportunity to see their new collaboration in action. Featuring Erin Burkholder and  Jeremy Gabbert, violins; Jeremy Bauman, viola; and Danny Poceta, cello.

They will perform Beethoven's String Quartet no. 10 ("Harp") and other works to be announced!

We will welcome open mic performers following the feature performance. Cover charge of $5 goes directly to support the members of the string quartet.

He’s performed at the Calgary Folk Music Festival, was a part of the inaugural Singer-Songwriter Residency at the Banff Centre, has recorded with Howard Bilerman (producer for Arcade Fire’s Funeral), shared songs with Jeff Hanna (of the Nitty Gritty Dirt Band), had music featured on both the CBC, has done a live show on BBC radio, and has performed north of the arctic circle. He’s a permanent member of Calgarian bands Rosalind and I Am The Mountain, and has performed with countless other groups from Alberta and BC. In early 2018 he toured the UK with Glasgow-based artist Carla J Easton, and in 2019 is planning on attended McGill University in Montreal, and will be releasing new material as a solo artist.

column8:
Timbre of Time (or, timbre de temps) An exploration of the spectral approach to music, originated fifty years ago in France by pioneer composers Gerard Grisey and Tristan Murail. Timbre was never a new word to the French, and the approach has been carried on by many other composers into modern day. Today we will be listening to these French composers’ work within the timbre of their time.


Also featuring music by Debussy and Jolivet, as well as Kaija Saariaho’s NoaNoa for flute and electronics — live electronics performed by composer Brian Garbet.

Trust us when we tell you that this is a gig you do not want to miss.  Strongly suggest you make a reservation for this one!\r\n\r\nRaised in a small prairie town, Christina grew up in a musical family where the sounds of southern rock, country, gospel and blues could often be heard on playing on her Dad’s stereo.  Her first live performance was at 5 years old, and she learned to play guitar at age 12.  In her teens, she became enamoured with artists like Etta James, Mavis Staples, Nina Simone, The Band, JJ Cale, and Bob Dylan.  In 2014, Christina went back to writing, recording and performing after taking a hiatus to raise her three daughters, one of whom has a cognitive disability. She recently released an original project called “Uncaged".

The Inglewood Night Market is a modern day market that occurs on a Friday once a month, from June to September in Calgary Alberta.

In 2019 our dates are June 7th, July 12th, August 9th, September 13th and September 14th (In September we do two nights both Friday and Saturday) we run from 5pm to 11pm each date.

Each event hosts over 50 local vendors selling diverse goods from handmade craftsmen items to vintage clothing, antiques & collectibles, artisan eats & more! You’ll also find food trucks, singer songwriters, bands, dancers, outdoor seating, a family friendly licensed area and other fun things to check out!

Our home is the beloved Inglewood Neighborhood just off 9th Avenue and 10th street!

column8: Come and listen to a voice described as “crisp, pure and powerful."  Danah-Lee’s last album, The Post Concussion Syndrome (December 1, 2017), has turned her very real-life experiences into songs. The album is a response to life unfolding – sometimes tragic and at other times euphoric.\r\n\r\nNOW - in 2019, the Ottawa Valley, Ontario-based singer songwriter has completed her latest EP, Sunshine & Bonbons (March 1, 2019). Danah worked with award winning producer Jordon Zadorozny (Courtney Love, Sam Roberts), and Phil Hulan (Belvue, Almost Kennedy), to record an album that is quite different than anything Danah has released before. Sunshine & Bonbons is one-part edgy, and one-part tug at your heart strings!

This promises to be a great evening of music!

Hole In The Hollow started as a solo project for Andy to be able to play to the softer side of his musical abilities. After going solo for a little while he decided to add members and create a full band sound. Adding Mackenzie’s vocals has brought depth and expanded harmonizing possibilities as well as it has deepened the stories told in the music. Chris’ bass allows for the music to be felt as well as heard, and Manuel’s drumming holds us all together and grabs the attention of listeners with unique fills.

column8:
This Frontier Needs Heroes is the moniker of singer-songwriter Brad
Lauretti, who in various forms and lineup changes, has spent the past 10
years playing shows all over the world. Logging thousands of miles in his
car, touring the greatest cities of North America and Europe, selling one
record at a time, making one fan at a time. This determination and DIY
ethos brought him on an epic journey around the world, playing listening
rooms, clubs, house concerts, and festival stages. One night with Brad will
run the gamut of all human emotions from humour, hedonism, activism and
heartbreaking sadness. From Folk-rock anthems, to indie folk, flares of
psychedelic, alt-country, to straight up storytelling you get it all in one
song. Influenced by songwriters like John Prine, Billy Bragg, Kris
Kristofferson, and Townes Van Zandt his timeless songs mix love, humor, and
protest seamlessly to get you through the tough times.

Tone Indbryn is a singer/songwriter who creates pieces woven from folk with mellow rock hints to support her lyrics laced with sardonic humour. She has performed in festivals, and local venues throughout BC, Ontario and Alberta, she is currently finishing off her 4th album   for 2019.

On Dial Tones and Pretty Notes, his latest full- length album, Graham Nicholas has created an emotionally resonant world inhabited by troubled and love-hungry characters. The album finds Nicholas honing in on his concise form of storytelling and refining his irreverent sense of humour.

column8:
When you come to the airport tomorrow at 09:00am (Mountain Time - US & Canada), please park in long-term parking and bring your parking ticket to be validated at reception on the mezzanine level (same level as food court). Reception is located directly above the WestJet domestic check-in counters. Darlene will validate your parking and let us know you are here.

We will have a quick conversation about what the program looks like and take you post-security to do a short performance (maybe 30-45 min.) to give you a feel for what the regular performance will be like. Unfortunately, you will not be able to busk during this trial performance, but we will pay you the $25 performance fee in cash.

Please bring government issued ID with you to get through security. We will have a Bose L1 sound system set-up with a mic and mic stand. 

Looking forward to meeting with you!

Sincerely, 
Jocelyn and Peggy

I perform as a solo act; with my acoustic Martin guitar, my vocals and usually a loop pedal, (for rhythm and harmonizing my vocals); all through a PA or my portable PA system. Because I play as a solo act, it's easy to set up and take down, and works perfectly in a festival atmosphere! I've played all around Calgary and Alberta, at venues like Brewsters, Vagabond, Half-Hitch Brewery, and have festival experience, (Rock Creek Music Festival, Bragg Creek Days). I have about 80 minutes of original music and up to six hours of cover songs! I'd love to work with your event and play as part of it, please don't hesitate to contact me with any questions! I have links to music, media, and more on my website as well. 

Thanks

- Grant Kanigan

column8: Two accomplished singer/songwriters from different parts of the world have come together in Calgary to form this unique acoustic folk/roots duo called Dublin2Durban. Gerry Madigan, on vocals and banjo, hails from Dublin in Ireland, where he was weaned on the booming folk scene of the seventies. Katie Windt, on vocals and guitar, comes from Durban in South Africa, where she was involved in its vibrant music scene with her own band.

Traditional West African music blends with the sounds of the world for a heartfelt, life-affirming fusion.

column5: Cornerstone Songwriters Cooperative hosted by Carolyn Harley and Co-hosted by
column8:
The Cornerstone Songwriters Cooperative!! 
The second Sunday of each month 1:00 - 3:00 
There will be time to visit and connect from 3-4 for anyone wanting to stay afterward. 
Carolyn Harley will be hosting this new event for songwriters and original music fans. This cozy venue will allow an intimate and casual way for songwriters to connect and create community. A different songwriter will co-host with Carolyn each month to perform and talk about their songwriting process. 
We will allow time for songwriters in attendance to perform their work and receive feed back if they wish. We are looking to create an opportunity for songwriters to get to know each other and share. 

Join Cornerstone Music Cafe in celebrating their for love original live music !!

column8:
Lanice Chep is a non-binary Okotoks singer-songwriter who has an affinity for all things honest and heartfelt while creating a relaxing coffee-shop-esque atmosphere for the audience. Beautifully  matched with modern folk guitar, their lyrics are soft and yielding and are deeply rooted in personal experiences.


Southern Alberta songstress Hanna Taylor  has a refreshingly powerful yet soft voice that is capable of shifting melodies into a world of their own. Having grown up between Canada and New Zealand, her lyrics reflect the small nuances of cultural disparities and leave the listener with either a sense of curiosity or a thought provoking story.

26-Hours of Bingeworthy Improv on Feb 28 & 29
The 26-Hour Improv Marathon returns! Beginning at 8pm on Feb 28 and ending 10pm Feb 29, we bring you 26 hours of nonstop improv. With a different show every hour, it’s wildly experimental and wildly fun. Stay for one, stay for all.
Admission to all shows is by donation (suggested amount $10 per show). Donate online or at the door.
Funds raised support our phenomenal Reactor Improv Festival, bringing in some of the world’s best improvisers.
Stay tuned for our full lineup to be announced in January 2020.

column8: A highly talented guitarist and a writer of songs that can touch the heart or tickle the funny bone – Neil Speers is an experienced performer based in Calgary. This summer he released his latest CD Snapshot Blues.

Skookkum is comprised of singers/songwriters Janine Bracewell & Jeff Kushner. It is the smaller, more acoustic sibling of Calgary band MoFaux. Their songs are about love and longing, joy & sadness and beautiful covers from Ryan Adams, Jeff Buckley and Emmylou Harris. Melodic songs and seamless harmonies.. a little shoegazing and a little folk...

Bacbruce is a rock-pop project of Luis Lamela and Diego Curcumelis. Based in Edmonton, Canada, “Just Worry!” is the latest EP release in 2018 and was played on local radio (NOW radio 102.3) and well received by online fans of the band. New EP "I Saw" to be released by the end 2019!!\r\n\r\nInfluenced by their diverse musical tastes, Meadow Drive puts a new spin on some of your favourite styles - everything from alternative to jazz, to 80's pop.

column8: David Dallas has been steadily building a name for himself as one of the up and coming guitarists of Alberta. A native Calgarian, David has spent most of his music career playing in the city he grew up in, as well as in the provinces’ capital. He has also performed in a variety of clubs, bars, and festivals around Alberta and in British Columbia. Some of the styles that he has dedicated his life to learning and performing include Jazz, Blues, Rock, Country, Americana, and Folk.  Join the David Dallas Group as they perform modern jazz arangments of contemporary classic songs.

column14: Grant Kanigan - Solo singer-songwriter. I use an acoustic Martin guitar, (with a pickup), a loop pedal, and vocals to create a unique, eclectic and enjoyable musical experience. Hailing from Calgary, Alberta, I've played bars, local events, private parties, corporate events, and festivals, including Waynestock, Beakerhead, and Bragg Creek days, among others. I would love to be a part of this years Lilac festival! I have over 90 minutes of original folk-rock songs and hundreds of covers in my catalogue! My Stagehand profile includes media and photos as well as a link to my website - which features video, pictures, information and more, as well as links to listen to my full-length album on streaming services like Spotify, iTunes and YouTube. I hope to hear from you soon! The only requirements I need are an electrical outlet for my loop system - otherwise, I'm good to just plug and play!

Admission to all shows is by donation (suggested amount $10 per show). Donate online or at the door.
Funds raised support our phenomenal Reactor Improv Festival, bringing in some of the world’s best improvisers.
Stay tuned for our full lineup to be announced in January 2020.

Aspen is thrilled to be hosting our second music night fundraiser 'A Little Night Music' on Thursday, March 26th! The event will take place at Festival Hall located in Inglewood and will feature incredible artists such as Remix: Powered by Revv52, Two Late to the Party, Laura Schoenberg Music and more!

One of the funds that 'A Little Night Music' will be supporting is Aspen's Flexible Wellness Fund. This fund was developed to cover costs for items and experiences that aren't always affordable for families living in poverty but are undeniably meaningful to the people that Aspen works with. To date this fund has provided many wellness opportunities including a McDonalds birthday party for a six year old boy, outfitting a youth for her first summer camp adventure and allowing for a grieving mother to receive a much needed massage.

More details go to https://www.aspenfamily.org/nightmusic

*** Update***

As the situation around COVID-19 has now evolved into a declared pandemic, we wanted to provide an update on the CDA’s current policies and the steps that we are taking. The health and safety of our people, and our ability to continue to support the downtown community is of the utmost importance to us. 

Our organization has activated the practice of social distancing to help contain the spread of COVID-19.  As such, the CDA office is closed to the public on a go-forward basis, and all programming and event activities have been cancelled indenfinetly.  Our work will continue online and remotely. We are looking forward to reconnecting in the near future about our relaunch kick-off activities.

Please note, that we will not be accepting any booking requests at this time, our schedule will be released when it is safe to do so for all involved parties.

Thank-you for your patience and support

column8: TAYLR provides sultry folk reflections, paired with floating melodies. She is versatile artist who provides the perfect soundtrack for the end of the night when you need to figure out if your date wants to kiss you or not. With TAYLR playing, your odds improve, just remember you need to ask first!\r\n\r\nMason Jenkins is an advocate and spokesperson for bringing back the "Calgary Wave" and tries embody the attitude of a very good dog. Jenkins is a transgender man, sharing stories of his adventures in gender and navigating the world as a retired lesbian. His songs are velvet paintings, delightfully campy, and welcomed in any grandmother's living room. Velvet paintings are built on darkness, just like Jenkins’ humour and insights. Contrast is what makes the highlights brighter, any dog could tell you that.

As the situation around COVID-19 has now evolved into a declared pandemic, we wanted to provide an update on the CDA’s current policies and the steps that we are taking. The health and safety of our people, and our ability to continue to support the downtown community is of the utmost importance to us.
